---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import problemMeme from "../img/problem_meme.gif";
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="center cover-internal">
  <h3>The Problem</h3>
  <Image
    p-fragment
    src={problemMeme}
    alt="problem meme"
    class="alter-image-size"
  />
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h4>
    <span class="text-cover"
      >Main problems with framework-specific components</span
    > 🚨
  </h4>
  <ul class="mid-dimension">
    <li p-fragment>
      📌 Vendor lock-in: components only work within that framework 🔗
    </li>
    <li p-fragment>
      📌 Costly rewrites if the framework changes or fades away ⚠️
    </li>
    <li p-fragment>📌 Risk of framework deprecation or discontinuation 🧩</li>
    <li p-fragment>
      📌 Reduced longevity: design system tied to framework lifecycle 🚫
    </li>
    <li p-fragment>
      📌 Slower adoption of new standards & browser features ⏳
    </li>
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p><b>VendorLockIn: often only with same framework version</b></p>
    <p>
      <b>maintenance</b>: Developers spend more time fixing issues and adapting
      to breaking changes, instead of building new features. This isn't just
      technical cost — it's also business cost. Slower delivery, higher budget
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide autoplay>
  <h3>
    <span class="current-gradient-sub-section"
      >Alright, thanks for the chaos!</span
    > 😅
  </h3>
  <h5 p-fragment style="text-align: end;">
    <span class="current-gradient-sub-section">…so, what's our next move?</span>
    🤔
  </h5>
</p-slide>
<style lang="scss">
  h4 {
    margin-block-end: 0.8em;
  }
  .cover-internal {
    img {
      --image-start-size: 6em;
      filter: none;
      opacity: 1;
      transform: none;
      height: var(--image-start-size);
    }
  }
</style>
